column1: As of the end of 2021, will total connected capacity of solar panels installed through the Shams Dubai program reach or exceed 400 MW?
column6: ['Technology', 'Environment']
Thanks @belikewater ! And well played!

Finally, some data! "Al Tayer noted that through its Shams Dubai initiative to connect photovoltaic solar systems on rooftops, DEWA has so far connected more than 6,880 photovoltaic installations on buildings in Dubai, with a total capacity of more than 365MW." https://www.wam.ae/en/details/1395303001375
I'm not seeing any recent info on this so maintaining a 1 in 4 chance.

I wish we could see more data on how installations went in Q3. Supply chain issues with goods and materials originating in China persist, but catastrophic problems due to the energy situation in China (e.g., with magnesium) have been avoided. I see that at least some solar panel suppliers in Dubai have plentiful supplies of solar panels, but prices have been going up worldwide, and as with everything, there is a demand curve that is surely not completely price inelastic. https://qz.com/2081333/supply-chain-chaos-threatens-the-growth-of-solar-energy/ I'm hedging slightly higher primarily because of uncertainty, but staying low because of increasing costs and supply chain issues. If it weren't for the Pandemic, I think it's very likely that growth in MW under the Shams Dubai program would have been larger than it has been so far this year, and I think it's extremely likely they would make it to 400MW by the end of the year. With all the economic dislocations of the pandemic, I think it will be very close (maybe even 395 to 399MW!), but I suspect that they won't quite reach 400MW, with the the slowdown in growth (relative to what it would have been like without the pandemic) likely increasing through Q4, commensurate with increasing global solar panel costs, materials costs, and shipping costs.
As of August they are at 298.7. Due to supply chain issues with both solar and construction materials they will not achieve the stated target
maybe belikewater is right that the likely supply chain troubles could hit before year end.

I'm revising my forecast even lower, as the news coming out of China gets worse. On top of a silicon shortage, there's a magnesium shortage, which will likely impact everything made with aluminum, including solar panels. https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2021-09-29/china-slashes-silicon-output-signaling-higher-solar-panel-costs https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2021-10-14/aluminum-makers-sound-the-alarm-about-u-s-magnesium-shortage
Down 5, following the crowd a bit and 1 in 4 seems about right for now.

Actually I am revising it a tad bit up, it seems there might be a seasonal trend that makes the build-out toward year-end quicker than the average pace for the year. Maybe summers are too hot for people to work on roofs or something.

I actually think the crowd is spot on when it comes to the chance here. It is more or less 20%. I just used the rate of build out form the last 5 intervals with data and made projections with each and only one of them lands me above 400MW. This made me think: Is there a way to compensate for previously high estimates? So if I had wrongly predicted 50% chance over the last 2 weeks and I actually believe it is 25%, can I then predict 0% for two weeks to "average out" my mistaken 50% predictions with 0% and give an average of 25%?

Just adjusting a bit downwards here as in fact numbers seem to indicate we might end up just short of 400MW. That said, I need to do some more analysis to see whether the small shortfall means a small or big movement away from 50-50 - I am trying to assess the different rates of build-out from the past to get an idea of the distribution around the mean production.

As I wrote below, I think this is a really tough forecast, with a 2nd degree polynomial fit predicting almost exactly 400 MW being achieved by the end of 2021. After thinking about it some more, I'm revising my forecast down because July's numbers were ever so slightly below trend and because the market for solar panels is really stretched taut and headed into much worse territory. If the solar panel market weren't taking a nose dive, I'd leave my forecast at 50/50, but the market has been bad and is soon going to get a lot worse.
Dropping 5 based on the excellent info provided by @belikewater here: https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1341565

From March 2021: "Dubai installed nearly 299 megawatts (MW) of rooftop solar photovoltaic (PV) capacity at the end of March under the Shams Dubai inititaive, a press statement by the Dubai Electricity and Water Authority (DEWA) said." https://www.zawya.com/mena/en/projects/story/PROJECTS_Dubai_installs_299_megawatts_of_rooftop_solar-ZAWYA20210414123842/

They were at 261.9 MW at the end of 2020, and according to this statement from April of this year they had hit 299. So that's a pace of 37.1 megawatts in 3 to 4 months. That pace will put them very close to 400 by year end. But it's just one data point, and the last two years the installed capacity has grown at a pace of around 95 MW a year which would put them at around 360 MW by year end. I'm guessing they'll beat that this year, but not sure they can hit 400.
A polynomial fit to progress from 2016 through 2020 yields almost exactly 400 MW for 2021. I'm not sure I should even try to forecast this.
Actually, there is no 400MW goal for EoY 2021 so I am going to just guess 50-50, we are very much on track for achieving roughly 400MW by year end.

Recent increases show they are pretty much on track. Moreover, and I hope I do not offend anyone, the Dubai authorities are likely to report they achieved the goal even if they were just a tad bit short of it - I do not think it is the most transparent country in the world. Or they will find a way to build the last few MWs so that they can tout their achievements. Maybe I should put this higher than 70%?
The listed rate of increase since 2016 does not indicate that they will reach 400.
If their labor market was as tight as everywhere else I don’t see them achieving that goal
